<scenario>
The agent A provided the following violation scenario:
The for loop uses a separate variable (urhn) in the third clause: for (urh = daemon->urh_tail; NULL != urh; urh = urhn). That variable (urhn) is assigned inside the loop body (urhn = urh->prev;). Clause 3 of MISRA C 2023 Rule 14.2 requires the third clause to modify only the loop counter and not to use objects that are modified in the loop body. Because the third-clause expression reads urhn which is written in the loop body, this violates Rule 14.2.
</scenario>

<instruction>
Judge whether the report is correct or not.
</instruction>

explanation:
The report is correct. MISRA C:2023 Rule 14.2 requires that the third clause of a for statement may only modify the loop counter and must not use objects that are modified in the loop body. In the reported loop:

for (urh = daemon->urh_tail; NULL != urh; urh = urhn)
{
  ...
  urhn = urh->prev;
  ...
}

the third clause reads urhn, but urhn is assigned inside the loop body. That means the third clause uses an object that is modified by the loop body, which violates Rule 14.2. (The likely reason the code does this is to capture the next/prev pointer prior to operations that may remove/modify urh, but that does not avoid the Rule 14.2 prohibition.)

Recommended remediation is to rewrite the loop so the loop-control update does not depend on a variable modified inside the body (for example use a while loop and perform urh = urhn as an explicit update after urhn is set, or compute the next pointer before entering a for-style update that does not read a body-modified object).
